.COM as a consulting company, and several ex-LOD members had accounts on the system. In the late 1990s, a root DNS server had an illicit new [[TLD]] of .LOD for over a year.  The business name \"LOD Communications\" arose sometime in the late 80s when Frank Carson (aka Basketball Jones - one of the few \"Unknown to the public\" LOD Members) registered the name & applied for a CT Tax ID to enable Marauder to get on the Bellcore technical document mailing list.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Great Hacker War]]\n*[[The Hacker Crackdown]]\n*[[Masters of Deception]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Public access legal records and transcripts===\n*US Government's Sentencing Memorandum, US v. Grant, Darden and Riggs, Criminal Action Number 1:90-CR-31, December 1990. (US Government v. \"Legion of Doom\")\n*LOD Technical Manuals and source\n*[http://www.textfiles.com/magazines/LOD/ The Legion of Doom/Hackers Technical Journal]\n\n{{Hacking in the 1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legion of Doom (Hacking)}}\n[[Category:Defunct American computer magazines]]\n[[Category:Legion of Doom (hacking)|*]]\n[[Category:Hacker magazines]]\n[[Category:Hacker groups]]\n", "name_user": "7luckymaurya", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legion_of_Doom_(hacking)"}
{"title_page": "Howell Davies", "text_new": "{{for|the Welsh rugby player of the 1910s|Howell Davies (rugby)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:Howell_Davies.jpg|thumb|Howell Davies]]\nSir (William) '''Howell Davies''' (13 December 1851 \u2013 26 October 1932) was a Welsh-born [[leather]] merchant and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Family==\nDavies was born in [[Narberth, Pembrokeshire|Narberth]]  in [[Pembrokeshire]], the son of Thomas Davies. He was educated privately. In 1882 he married Ada Mary Hosegood, the daughter of a [[Bristol]] [[Justice of the Peace]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref>  Lady Davies died in 1948 at the age of 91.<ref>The Times, 10 February 1948</ref> They had one son and three daughters. Their son was [[Lt-Col]]. Owen Stanley Davies [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] who died in 1926 of wounds he received in the Great War, having undergone many operations. Their great-grandson is the writer [[Antony Woodward]]. By religion Davies was a [[Methodist|Wesleyan Methodist]].<ref>''Minutes of Several Conversations at the Yearly Conference of People Called Methodists'', published by the Wesleyan Methodist Church, 1908</ref>\n\n==Business==\nDavies moved to Bristol and established himself in the leather trade, eventually becoming a highly successful [[Tanning (leather)|tannery]] owner and leather merchant employing a large workforce.<ref>David J Jeremy, ''Religion, Business, and Wealth in Modern Britain''; Routledge, 1998 p.75</ref> He also acquired directorships and was a Director of the UK Temperance and General Provident Institution.<ref>The Times, 13 April 1933</ref>\n\n==Local politics==\nLike many successful [[Victorian era|Victorian]] and [[Edwardian]] businessmen, Davies was eager to serve his community through municipal politics and at the same time provide himself a stepping-stone to further advancement.  He first joined [[Bristol City Council]] in 1884 and was made an [[Alderman]] in 1889. He was elected [[Mayor]] of Bristol in 1896. He served for a time as Leader of the Liberal Party on Bristol City Council and was sometime President of the [[Chamber of Commerce]].<ref>''General Election, Wales & Monmouthshire 1906 \u2013 a Souvenir'': Liberal Party, 1906; http://lloydgeorgesociety.org.uk/resources/sites/84.234.17.197-4611481cc83403.08117414/Welsh+Liberal+MPs+elected+in+1906.pdf</ref> During his time on the Council Davies acquired extensive Municipal experience being Chairman of Bristol Docks Committee between 1899 and 1908 and was Chairman during the construction of, and at the time of the opening of the Royal Edward Dock which was formally opened by King [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]] in July 1908. Davies was also Chairman of Bristol Finance Committee, 1902\u201329. For more than 46 years Davies took a leading role in political life of the city of Bristol and in 1908 he was [[knighted]] for municipal services in the King's birthday honours list.<ref name=times>The Times, 27 October 1932</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary politics==\nDavies first stood for [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1900]], the so-called [[Khaki election]].<ref>John Latimer, ''The Annals of Bristol in the Nineteenth Century (concluded) 1887-1900''; W George\u2019s Sons, 1902 p,97</ref> He had been adopted as the Liberal candidate for [[Bristol South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol South]] before the sitting MP (Sir Edward Stock Hill) had decided to retire.<ref>The Times, 18 September 1900</ref> His [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] opponent was [[Walter Hume Long]].\n\nLong won that election and even though the political tide had turned decisively against them by the time of the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] the Conservatives believed they would hold Bristol South, evenly if only narrowly.<ref>The Times, 12 December 1906</ref> However Bristol South was one of many unexpected gains for the Liberals in their 1906 general election landslide victory. The Liberals took three of the four Bristol seats at the election and as late as 14 January, Liberal [[Chief Whip]], [[Herbert Gladstone]] had confidently expected Walter Long to hold on in Bristol South.<ref>A K Russell, ''Liberal Landslide: The General Election of 1906''; David & Charles, 1973 p.153</ref> However Davies beat Long with a majority of 2,692 votes.<ref>The Times, 11 January 1910</ref> He held the seat at the next election in [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] albeit by the narrow margin of 271 votes.<ref>The Times, 12 November 1910</ref> As a consequence, Davies expected a hard-fought contest at the [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|December 1910 election]]. Divisions in the Bristol Unionist ranks may have helped divert Tory attentions from the real fight. H Chatterton who had stood for the Conservatives in January 1910 was dropped by the Tories in favour of a different candidate and decided to put himself forward as an Independent Unionist, only withdrawing from the election at the last moment.<ref>The Times, 30 November 1910</ref> In the end Davies was able to hold his seat over the new Conservative candidate J T Francombe with a majority of 138.<ref>The Times, 5 December 1910</ref>\n\nDavies never held ministerial office but he was appointed to the important Parliamentary [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]] on National Expenditure in 1920.\n\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] Davies was the representative of the Coalition government and was opposed only by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate [[Thomas Lewis (Bristol politician)|Thomas Lewis]], over whom he had a majority of  7,352 votes. He stood down from Parliament at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] but continued to play a part in Liberal politics, representing the South West on the National Liberal Council.<ref>The Times, 26 January 1923</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDavies died at Bristol on 26 October 1932,<ref name=times/> aged 80.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-william-davies  | Howell Davies }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bristol South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol South]]\n | years  = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\n | before = [[Walter Long, 1st Viscount Long|Walter Long]]\n | after  = [[Beddoe Rees]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, William Howell}}\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:1851 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Narberth]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Bristol]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Welsh rugby player of the 1910s|Howell Davies (rugby)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:Howell_Davies.jpg|thumb|Howell Davies]]\nSir (William) '''Howell Davies''' (13 December 1851 \u2013 26 October 1932) was a Welsh-born [[leather]] merchant and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Family==\nDavies was born in [[Narberth, Pembrokeshire|Narberth]]  in [[Pembrokeshire]], the son of Thomas Davies. He was educated privately. In 1882 he married Ada Mary Hosegood, the daughter of a [[Bristol]] [[Justice of the Peace]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref>  Lady Davies died in 1948 at the age of 91.<ref>The Times, 10 February 1948</ref> They had one son and three daughters. Their son was [[Lt-Col]]. Owen Stanley Davies [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] who died in 1926 of wounds he received in the Great War, having undergone many operations. Their great-grandson is the writer [[Antony Woodward]]. By religion Davies was a [[Methodist|Wesleyan Methodist]].<ref>''Minutes of Several Conversations at the Yearly Conference of People Called Methodists'', published by the Wesleyan Methodist Church, 1908</ref>\n\n==Business==\nDavies moved to Bristol and established himself in the leather trade, eventually becoming a highly successful [[Tanning (leather)|tannery]] owner and leather merchant employing a large workforce.<ref>David J Jeremy, ''Religion, Business, and Wealth in Modern Britain''; Routledge, 1998 p.75</ref> He also acquired directorships and was a Director of the UK Temperance and General Provident Institution.<ref>The Times, 13 April 1933</ref>\n\n==Local politics==\nLike many successful [[Victorian era|Victorian]] and [[Edwardian]] businessmen, Davies was eager to serve his community through municipal politics and at the same time provide himself a stepping-stone to further advancement.  He first joined [[Bristol City Council]] in 1884 and was made an [[Alderman]] in 1889. He was elected [[Mayor]] of Bristol in 1896. He served for a time as Leader of the Liberal Party on Bristol City Council and was sometime President of the [[Chamber of Commerce]].<ref>''General Election, Wales & Monmouthshire 1906 \u2013 a Souvenir'': Liberal Party, 1906; http://lloydgeorgesociety.org.uk/resources/sites/84.234.17.197-4611481cc83403.08117414/Welsh+Liberal+MPs+elected+in+1906.pdf</ref> During his time on the Council Davies acquired extensive Municipal experience being Chairman of Bristol Docks Committee between 1899 and 1908 and was Chairman during the construction of, and at the time of the opening of the Royal Edward Dock which was formally opened by King [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]] in July 1908. Davies was also Chairman of Bristol Finance Committee, 1902\u201329. For more than 46 years Davies took a leading role in political life of the city of Bristol and in 1908 he was [[knighted]] for municipal services in the King\u2019s birthday honours list.<ref name=times>The Times, 27 October 1932</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary politics==\nDavies first stood for [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1900]], the so-called [[Khaki election]].<ref>John Latimer, ''The Annals of Bristol in the Nineteenth Century (concluded) 1887-1900''; W George\u2019s Sons, 1902 p,97</ref> He had been adopted as the Liberal candidate for [[Bristol South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol South]] before the sitting MP (Sir Edward Stock Hill) had decided to retire.<ref>The Times, 18 September 1900</ref> His [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] opponent was [[Walter Hume Long]].\n\nLong won that election and even though the political tide had turned decisively against them by the time of the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] the Conservatives believed they would hold Bristol South, evenly if only narrowly.<ref>The Times, 12 December 1906</ref> However Bristol South was one of many unexpected gains for the Liberals in their 1906 general election landslide victory. The Liberals took three of the four Bristol seats at the election and as late as 14 January, Liberal [[Chief Whip]], [[Herbert Gladstone]] had confidently expected Walter Long to hold on in Bristol South.<ref>A K Russell, ''Liberal Landslide: The General Election of 1906''; David & Charles, 1973 p.153</ref> However Davies beat Long with a majority of 2,692 votes.<ref>The Times, 11 January 1910</ref> He held the seat at the next election in [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] albeit by the narrow margin of 271 votes.<ref>The Times, 12 November 1910</ref> As a consequence, Davies expected a hard fought contest at the [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|December 1910 election]]. Divisions in the Bristol Unionist ranks may have helped divert Tory attentions from the real fight. H Chatterton who had stood for the Conservatives in January 1910 was dropped by the Tories in favour of a different candidate and decided to put himself forward as an Independent Unionist, only withdrawing from the election at the last moment.<ref>The Times, 30 November 1910</ref> In the end Davies was able to hold his seat over the new Conservative candidate J T Francombe with a majority of 138.<ref>The Times, 5 December 1910</ref>\n\nDavies never held ministerial office but he was appointed to the important Parliamentary [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]] on National Expenditure in 1920.\n\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] Davies was the representative of the Coalition government and was opposed only by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate [[Thomas Lewis (Bristol politician)|Thomas Lewis]], over whom he had a majority of  7,352 votes. He stood down from Parliament at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] but continued to play a part in Liberal politics, representing the South West on the National Liberal Council.<ref>The Times, 26 January 1923</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDavies died at Bristol on 26 October 1932,<ref name=times/> aged 80.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-william-davies  | Howell Davies }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bristol South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol South]]\n | years  = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\n | before = [[Walter Long, 1st Viscount Long|Walter Long]]\n | after  = [[Beddoe Rees]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, William Howell}}\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:1851 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Narberth]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Bristol]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: a hard fought \u2192 a hard-fought, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howell_Davies"}
{"title_page": "Ellis Davies", "text_new": "{{for|the Welsh priest and antiquarian|Ellis Davies (priest)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Ellis William Davies.jpg|thumb|right|Ellis William Davies]]\n'''Ellis William Davies''' (12 April 1871 \u2013 29 April 1939) was a Welsh [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and later, briefly, [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|Liberal National]] politician and lawyer.\n\n==Early life and work==\nDavies was born at Gerlan, [[Bethesda, Gwynedd|Bethesda]], [[Caernarfonshire]], the son of David Davies a quarry official.<ref>https://biography.wales/article/s3-DAVI-WIL-1871?query=Liberal+MP&field=content</ref> He was educated in Bethesda and at [[Liverpool College]]. He worked as a clerk in insurance offices in [[Wrexham]] and [[Sheffield]] until he qualified as a [[solicitor]] in 1899. He passed his final [[Law Society]] examination with first-class honours, winning the Law Society prize in 1899, after which he established a law practice in [[Caernarfon]] where he lived for the rest of his life.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> He was also director of several companies and solicitor for the [[North Wales Quarrymen's Union]]. He died at Caernarfon in 1939.<ref>The Times, 1 May 1939</ref> He founded the Caernarfon solicitor firm - 'Ellis-Davies and Co' that is still in existence today and has his great grandson as one of the partners.\n\n==Politics==\nA political radical, Davies was elected to Caernarfonshire [[County Council]] in 1904, later becoming an [[alderman]]. He entered [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] in June 1906 when he was returned unopposed in a [[by-election]] for the [[Eifion (UK Parliament constituency)|Eifion]] division of Caernarfonshire, when the former [[Member of Parliament]] [[John Bryn Roberts]] was appointed a [[Judiciary of England and Wales|county court judge]]. Eifion had been held by Roberts, a Liberal in the [[Gladstonian Liberalism|Gladstonian]] tradition, since its creation for the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]] and at the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] Roberts had also been returned unopposed. Davies retained the Eifion constituency until [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]].\n\nDuring his years in Parliament, Davies sat on committees investigating land reform, the jury system, reform of the electoral system, compulsory purchases by local authorities, and reform of the [[House of Lords]]. He returned to Parliament as MP for [[Denbigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Denbigh]] in [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]], but resigned in 1929 on grounds of ill health. In 1932, he was prominent in the discussions of the [[Presbyterian Church of Wales]] on formulating a parliamentary bill relating to the church.<ref>[http://www.archivesnetworkwales.info/cgi-bin/anw/search2?coll_id=646&inst_id=1&term=ellis%20william%20davies Archives Network Wales - Ellis W. Davies Papers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Davies and Lloyd George==\nDuring the First World War, Davies was one of a number of Welsh MPs who broke with Prime Minister [[David Lloyd George]] over his conduct of the war. Davies regarded Lloyd George's ministry as bellicose and illiberal, conflicting with his own strongly held [[pacifist]] and pro-labour views.<ref>Emyr Price, ''David Lloyd George'', University of Wales Press, 2006; p.199</ref> Although Ellis Davies was never really close to Lloyd George he knew him quite well being a [[Caernarfonshire]] MP and his journal records a number of occasions when they discussed political questions<ref>[[John Grigg (writer)]], ''Lloyd George: The People\u2019s Champion, 1902-1911'':Penguin, 1997: p373</ref> or worked together on specific projects.<ref>John Grigg, ''Lloyd George: From Peace to War, 1912-1916'': Penguin, 1997: p42</ref> At the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] Davies, as a supporter of the [[H. H. Asquith|Asquithian Liberals]], did not receive [[The Coalition Coupon|the coalition coupon]] and was heavily defeated, coming bottom of the poll.<ref>[[K O Morgan]], ''Wales in British Politics, 1868-1922'': University of Wales Press, 1963, p.283</ref>\n\n==Labour and Liberal Nationals==\nDavies joined the Labour Party in 1936, only to leave early in 1939 because of its foreign policy. He believed that [[Neville Chamberlain]]\u2019s policy of [[appeasement]] was more likely to keep the peace than Labour's support for intervention abroad. As a supporter of [[social reform]], he felt that there was plenty of work to be done to improve social conditions at home and this could not be done if the country was at war. He then chose to associate himself with the Liberal Nationals, the allies of Chamberlain's Conservative government, although at the age of 68 years it was probably not in the hope of finding another seat.<ref>The Times,9 February 1939</ref>\n\n==Papers==\nThe papers of Ellis Davies, 1889\u20131939, comprising his diaries, journals, correspondence, press cuttings, addresses, articles and memoirs, together with printed and typescript memoranda, reports, policy documents and official publications are deposited at the [[National Library of Wales]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-ellis-davies | Ellis Davies }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Bryn Roberts]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Eifion (UK Parliament constituency)|Eifion]]\n | years  = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Denbigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Denbigh]]\n | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]] \u2013 [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]\n | before = [[John Cledwyn Davies]]\n | after  = [[Henry Morris-Jones]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=President of the [[Welsh Liberal Federation]]|years=1921&ndash;1922|before=''New position''|after=[[Henry Gladstone]]}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairman of the [[Welsh Liberal Federation]]|years=1922&ndash;1925|before=?|after=[[John Hinds (politician)|John Hinds]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Ellis William}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:People from Caernarfonshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Liverpool College]]\n[[Category:Welsh solicitors]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (UK, 1931) politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Welsh priest and antiquarian|Ellis Davies (priest)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Ellis William Davies.jpg|thumb|right|Ellis William Davies]]\n'''Ellis William Davies''' (12 April 1871 \u2013 29 April 1939) was a Welsh [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and later, briefly, [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|Liberal National]] politician and lawyer.\n\n==Early life and work==\nDavies was born at Gerlan, [[Bethesda, Gwynedd|Bethesda]], [[Caernarfonshire]], the son of David Davies a quarry official.<ref>https://biography.wales/article/s3-DAVI-WIL-1871?query=Liberal+MP&field=content</ref> He was educated in Bethesda and at [[Liverpool College]]. He worked as a clerk in insurance offices in [[Wrexham]] and [[Sheffield]] until he qualified as a [[solicitor]] in 1899. He passed his final [[Law Society]] examination with first-class honours, winning the Law Society prize in 1899, after which he established a law practice in [[Caernarfon]] where he lived for the rest of his life.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> He was also director of several companies and solicitor for the [[North Wales Quarrymen's Union]]. He died at Caernarfon in 1939.<ref>The Times, 1 May 1939</ref> He founded the Caernarfon solicitor firm - 'Ellis-Davies and Co' that is still in existence today and has his great grandson as one of the partners.\n\n==Politics==\nA political radical, Davies was elected to Caernarfonshire [[County Council]] in 1904, later becoming an [[alderman]]. He entered [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] in June 1906 when he was returned unopposed in a [[by-election]] for the [[Eifion (UK Parliament constituency)|Eifion]] division of Caernarfonshire, when the former [[Member of Parliament]] [[John Bryn Roberts]] was appointed a [[Judiciary of England and Wales|county court judge]]. Eifion had been held by Roberts, a Liberal in the [[Gladstonian Liberalism|Gladstonian]] tradition, since its creation for the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]] and at the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] Roberts had also been returned unopposed. Davies retained the Eifion constituency until [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]].\n\nDuring his years in Parliament, Davies sat on committees investigating land reform, the jury system, reform of the electoral system, compulsory purchases by local authorities, and reform of the [[House of Lords]]. He returned to Parliament as MP for [[Denbigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Denbigh]] in [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]], but resigned in 1929 on grounds of ill health. In 1932, he was prominent in the discussions of the [[Presbyterian Church of Wales]] on formulating a parliamentary bill relating to the church.<ref>[http://www.archivesnetworkwales.info/cgi-bin/anw/search2?coll_id=646&inst_id=1&term=ellis%20william%20davies Archives Network Wales - Ellis W. Davies Papers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Davies and Lloyd George==\nDuring the First World War, Davies was one of a number of Welsh MPs who broke with Prime Minister [[David Lloyd George]] over his conduct of the war. Davies regarded Lloyd George\u2019s ministry as bellicose and illiberal, conflicting with his own strongly held [[pacifist]] and pro-labour views.<ref>Emyr Price, ''David Lloyd George'', University of Wales Press, 2006; p.199</ref> Although Ellis Davies was never really close to Lloyd George he knew him quite well being a [[Caernarfonshire]] MP and his journal records a number of occasions when they discussed political questions<ref>[[John Grigg (writer)]], ''Lloyd George: The People\u2019s Champion, 1902-1911'':Penguin, 1997: p373</ref> or worked together on specific projects.<ref>John Grigg, ''Lloyd George: From Peace to War, 1912-1916'': Penguin, 1997: p42</ref> At the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]] Davies, as a supporter of the [[H. H. Asquith|Asquithian Liberals]], did not receive [[The Coalition Coupon|the coalition coupon]] and was heavily defeated, coming bottom of the poll.<ref>[[K O Morgan]], ''Wales in British Politics, 1868-1922'': University of Wales Press, 1963, p.283</ref>\n\n==Labour and Liberal Nationals==\nDavies joined the Labour Party in 1936, only to leave early in 1939 because of its foreign policy. He believed that [[Neville Chamberlain]]\u2019s policy of [[appeasement]] was more likely to keep the peace than Labour\u2019s support for intervention abroad. As a supporter of [[social reform]], he felt that there was plenty of work to be done to improve social conditions at home and this could not be done if the country was at war. He then chose to associate himself with the Liberal Nationals, the allies of Chamberlain's Conservative government, although at the age of 68 years it was probably not in the hope of finding another seat.<ref>The Times,9 February 1939</ref>\n\n==Papers==\nThe papers of Ellis Davies, 1889\u20131939, comprising his diaries, journals, correspondence, press cuttings, addresses, articles and memoirs, together with printed and typescript memoranda, reports, policy documents and official publications are deposited at the [[National Library of Wales]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-ellis-davies | Ellis Davies }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Bryn Roberts]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Eifion (UK Parliament constituency)|Eifion]]\n | years  = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Denbigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Denbigh]]\n | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]] \u2013 [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]\n | before = [[John Cledwyn Davies]]\n | after  = [[Henry Morris-Jones]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=President of the [[Welsh Liberal Federation]]|years=1921&ndash;1922|before=''New position''|after=[[Henry Gladstone]]}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairman of the [[Welsh Liberal Federation]]|years=1922&ndash;1925|before=?|after=[[John Hinds (politician)|John Hinds]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Ellis William}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:People from Caernarfonshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Liverpool College]]\n[[Category:Welsh solicitors]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (UK, 1931) politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)",