{"title_page": "Pete Curran", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n[[File:Pete Curran.png|thumb|Curran, about 1905]]\n'''Peter Francis Curran''' (28 March 1860 \u2013 14 February 1910) was a [[British people|British]] [[trade unionist]] and [[politician]].\n\nBorn '''Patrick Francis Curran''' in [[Glasgow]], to a [[Catholic]] family of [[Irish people|Irish]] origin, Curran became known as \"Pete\" at an early age. He left school at the age of eleven, training as a blacksmith and working at a steel plant.<ref name=\"reformer\">''The Reformers' Year Book: 1908'', p.231</ref><ref name=\"odnb\">\"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/45908 Curran, Peter Francis]\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref>  Always interested in politics, he joined the [[Irish Land League]], but was impressed by [[Henry George]]'s speeches, and transferred to the [[Scottish Land Restoration League]] in 1880. He married in 1881, and around this time also joined the [[Social Democratic Federation]] (SDF).<ref name=\"reformer\" /><ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nLate in the 1880s, Curran moved to [[London]] to work at the [[Royal Arsenal]]. He worked with [[Will Thorne]] to found the [[National Union of Gasworkers and General Labourers]], and in 1889, he became the union's full-time secretary for the West of England. He was convicted of intimidation during a dispute in [[Plymouth]], but this was overturned in the [[Court of Appeal]] in the famous case ''Curran v. Treleaven''.  With newfound fame, he moved back to London to take up the post of national organiser of the gasworkers' union.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nWhile remaining a member of the SDF, Curran joined the [[Fabian Society]] and was a founder member of the [[Independent Labour Party]] (ILP). He was a member of the ILP's [[National Administrative Council]] from 1893\u201398, and stood for the party in [[Barrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow]] at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]], but won only 6.9% of the votes cast.  His next contest was the [[1897 Barnsley by-election]], where he took just over 1,000 votes, only 9.7% of the total, and was attacked by [[Ben Pickard]], General Secretary of the [[Yorkshire Miners' Association]], for his socialist politics, and with claims that he had abandoned his wife.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nCurran married his second wife, [[Marian Barry]], a prominent women's labour activist, by 1898, and the couple had two sons and two daughters. Around this time, the couple were active opponents of the [[Second Boer War]], and Curran resigned from the Fabian Society in protest at its support for the conflict.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nIn 1899, Curran was a founder of the [[General Federation of Trade Unions (UK)|General Federation of Trade Unions]] (GFTU) serving as its first chairman. Although he was well known for his passionate speech at [[Trades Union Congress]] (TUC) meetings, he was privately dismissive of its leadership, and hoped that the GFTU would provide a way for unions to bypass and possibly supersede it. He was also prominent in the formation of the [[Labour Representation Committee (1900)|Labour Representation Committee]] (LRC), forerunner of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], which he saw as sharing the same aims as the GFTU.  In 1905, he arranged the creation of the Joint Board of the TUC, GFTU and LRC, and this marked the period in which the GFTU enjoyed the greatest influence.<ref>Alice Prochaska, ''History of the General Federation of Trade Unions: 1899-1980'', pp.19-20</ref>\n\nCurran stood for the LRC in [[Jarrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Jarrow]] at the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]].  Although he was narrowly defeated in a contest against the sitting [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] MP, he stood again at the [[1907 Jarrow by-election]]. On this occasion, he also faced [[Unionist Party (UK)|Unionist Party]] and [[Irish Nationalist Party|Irish Nationalist]] opposition, and these candidates took enough of the Liberal vote that he won the seat.<ref name=\"odnb\" /><ref>Stephen Lowrey, \"[https://www.societies.ncl.ac.uk/pgfnewcastle/files/2015/05/Lowrey-Pete-Curran.pdf Pete Curran and the Jarrow Parliamentary By-Election of 1907]\"</ref>\n\nBy this time, Curran was in poor health, principally due to his drinking. He was arrested and fined in 1909 for being drunk and incapable, and he developed [[cirrhosis of the liver]]. He lost his seat in another close contest at the [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910 general election]], and died shortly afterwards, aged 49.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = Member of Parliament for [[Jarrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Jarrow]]\n| years  = [[1907 Jarrow by-election|1907]] \u2013 [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|1910]]\n| before = [[Sir Charles Palmer, 1st Baronet|Charles Palmer]]\n| after  = [[Godfrey Palmer]]\n}}\n{{s-npo|union}}\n{{succession box|title=President of the [[National Union of Gasworkers and General Labourers]]|years=1894\u20131910|before=Will Watkinson|after=[[J. E. Smith]]}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Trades Union Congress]] representative to the [[American Federation of Labour]]|years=1900|with=[[John Weir (trade unionist)|John Weir]]|before=[[James Haslam]] and [[Alexander Wilkie]]|after=[[Francis Chandler]] and [[Ben Tillett]]}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairman of the [[General Federation of Trade Unions (UK)|General Federation of Trade Unions]]|years=1899 \u2013 1910|before=''New position''|after=[[Allan Gee]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curran, Pete}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:Georgists]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the General Federation of Trade Unions (UK)]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Federation members]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n[[File:Pete Curran.png|thumb|Curran, about 1905]]\n'''Peter Francis Curran''' (28 March 1860 \u2013 14 February 1910) was a [[British people|British]] [[trade unionist]] and [[politician]].\n\nBorn '''Patrick Francis Curran''' in [[Glasgow]], to a [[Catholic]] family of [[Irish people|Irish]] origin, Curran became known as \"Pete\" at an early age. He left school at the age of eleven, training as a blacksmith and working at a steel plant.<ref name=\"reformer\">''The Reformers' Year Book: 1908'', p.231</ref><ref name=\"odnb\">\"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/45908 Curran, Peter Francis]\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref>  Always interested in politics, he joined the [[Irish Land League]], but was impressed by [[Henry George]]'s speeches, and transferred to the [[Scottish Land Restoration League]] in 1880. He married in 1881, and around this time also joined the [[Social Democratic Federation]] (SDF).<ref name=\"reformer\" /><ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nLate in the 1880s, Curran moved to [[London]] to work at the [[Royal Arsenal]]. He worked with [[Will Thorne]] to found the [[National Union of Gasworkers and General Labourers]], and in 1889, he became the union's full-time secretary for the West of England. He was convicted of intimidation during a dispute in [[Plymouth]], but this was overturned in the [[Court of Appeal]] in the famous case ''Curran v. Treleaven''.  With newfound fame, he moved back to London to take up the post of national organiser of the gasworkers' union.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nWhile remaining a member of the SDF, Curran joined the [[Fabian Society]] and was a founder member of the [[Independent Labour Party]] (ILP). He was a member of the ILP's [[National Administrative Council]] from 1893-98, and stood for the party in [[Barrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow]] at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]], but won only 6.9% of the votes cast.  His next contest was the [[1897 Barnsley by-election]], where he took just over 1,000 votes, only 9.7% of the total, and was attacked by [[Ben Pickard]], General Secretary of the [[Yorkshire Miners' Association]], for his socialist politics, and with claims that he had abandoned his wife.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nCurran married his second wife, [[Marian Barry]], a prominent women's labour activist, by 1898, and the couple had two sons and two daughters. Around this time, the couple were active opponents of the [[Second Boer War]], and Curran resigned from the Fabian Society in protest at its support for the conflict.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\nIn 1899, Curran was a founder of the [[General Federation of Trade Unions (UK)|General Federation of Trade Unions]] (GFTU) serving as its first chairman. Although he was well known for his passionate speech at [[Trades Union Congress]] (TUC) meetings, he was privately dismissive of its leadership, and hoped that the GFTU would provide a way for unions to bypass and possibly supersede it. He was also prominent in the formation of the [[Labour Representation Committee (1900)|Labour Representation Committee]] (LRC), forerunner of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], which he saw as sharing the same aims as the GFTU.  In 1905, he arranged the creation of the Joint Board of the TUC, GFTU and LRC, and this marked the period in which the GFTU enjoyed the greatest influence.<ref>Alice Prochaska, ''History of the General Federation of Trade Unions: 1899-1980'', pp.19-20</ref>\n\nCurran stood for the LRC in [[Jarrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Jarrow]] at the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]].  Although he was narrowly defeated in a contest against the sitting [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] MP, he stood again at the [[1907 Jarrow by-election]]. On this occasion, he also faced [[Unionist Party (UK)|Unionist Party]] and [[Irish Nationalist Party|Irish Nationalist]] opposition, and these candidates took enough of the Liberal vote that he won the seat.<ref name=\"odnb\" /><ref>Stephen Lowrey, \"[https://www.societies.ncl.ac.uk/pgfnewcastle/files/2015/05/Lowrey-Pete-Curran.pdf Pete Curran and the Jarrow Parliamentary By-Election of 1907]\"</ref>\n\nBy this time, Curran was in poor health, principally due to his drinking. He was arrested and fined in 1909 for being drunk and incapable, and he developed [[cirrhosis of the liver]]. He lost his seat in another close contest at the [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910 general election]], and died shortly afterwards, aged 49.<ref name=\"odnb\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = Member of Parliament for [[Jarrow (UK Parliament constituency)|Jarrow]]\n| years  = [[1907 Jarrow by-election|1907]] \u2013 [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|1910]]\n| before = [[Sir Charles Palmer, 1st Baronet|Charles Palmer]]\n| after  = [[Godfrey Palmer]]\n}}\n{{s-npo|union}}\n{{succession box|title=President of the [[National Union of Gasworkers and General Labourers]]|years=1894\u20131910|before=Will Watkinson|after=[[J. E. Smith]]}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Trades Union Congress]] representative to the [[American Federation of Labour]]|years=1900|with=[[John Weir (trade unionist)|John Weir]]|before=[[James Haslam]] and [[Alexander Wilkie]]|after=[[Francis Chandler]] and [[Ben Tillett]]}}\n{{succession box|title=Chairman of the [[General Federation of Trade Unions (UK)|General Federation of Trade Unions]]|years=1899 \u2013 1910|before=''New position''|after=[[Allan Gee]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curran, Pete}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:Georgists]]\