{"title_page": "Thomas Cairns", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Thomas_Cairns.jpg|right|]]\n'''Thomas Ashley Cairns''' JP (1854 \u2013 3 September 1908)<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|n|1|date=March 2012}}</ref> was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician who served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-upon-Tyne]] from the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] until his death two years later due to diabetes,<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n|last=Craig\n|first=F. W. S.\n|authorlink=F. W. S. Craig\n|title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n|origyear=1974\n|edition=2nd\n|year=1989\n|publisher=Parliamentary Research Services\n|location=Chichester\n|isbn=0-900178-27-2\n|page=157\n}}</ref> aged 69.<ref name=\"rayment\" />\n\n==Background==\nCairns was born in Sunderland, the son of Thomas Cairns of Forfarshire. He was educated privately. In 1880 he married Isabella Dixon.<ref name=\"Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1907\">Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1907</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nCairns was chief partner of Cairns, Noble & Co., shipowners and merchants. He was Vice President of the Shipowners International Association.<ref name=\"The Liberal Year Book, 1907\">The Liberal Year Book, 1907</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCairns was a member of the Newcastle School Board from 1892\u201399. He was elected to Newcastle City Council in 1896. He was appointed as a [[Justice of the peace]] for Newcastle. He was active in the Liberal Party as Vice Chairman of the Executive Committee of the Northern Liberal Federation.<ref name=\"The Liberal Year Book, 1907\"/> He was Liberal candidate for the two member Newcastle-upon-Tyne division at the 1906 General Election. He ran in tandem with a labour candidate and together they took both seats from the Conservatives.<ref>British Parliamentary Election Results 1885-1918, FWS Craig</ref> Cairns was in favour of housing reform, social legislation and [[Women's suffrage in the United Kingdom|Women's suffrage]].<ref name=\"Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1907\"/>\n\n===Electoral record===\n{{Election box begin|title=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|General election January 1906]]<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Labour Representation Committee (1900)\n|candidate={{Y}} [[Walter Hudson (politician)|Walter Hudson]]\n|votes=18,869\n|percentage=31.1\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate={{Y}}Thomas Cairns\n|votes=18,423\n|percentage=30.5\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Walter Richard Plummer]]\n|votes=11,942\n|percentage=19.8\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Sir George Renwick, 1st Baronet|George Renwick]]\n|votes=11,223\n|percentage=18.6\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes=\n|percentage=84.6\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=6,927\n|percentage=11.3\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n|winner=Labour Representation Committee (1900)\n|loser=Conservative Party (UK)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=6,481\n|percentage=10.7\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n|winner=Liberal Party (UK)\n|loser=Conservative Party (UK)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-thomas-cairns|Thomas Cairns }}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-upon-Tyne]]\n|years=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[1908 Newcastle-upon-Tyne by-election|1908]]\n|with=[[Walter Hudson (politician)|Walter Hudson]]\n|before=[[Sir George Renwick, 1st Baronet|George Renwick]] and <br />[[Walter Richard Plummer|Sir Walter Plummer]]\n|after=[[Sir George Renwick, 1st Baronet|George Renwick]] and <br />[[Walter Hudson (politician)|Walter Hudson]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Craig, James}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Thomas_Cairns.jpg|right|]]\n'''Thomas Ashley Cairns''' JP (1854 \u2013 3 September 1908)<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|n|1|date=March 2012}}</ref> was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician who served as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-upon-Tyne]] from the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] until his death two years later due to diabetes,<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n|last=Craig\n|first=F. W. S.\n|authorlink=F. W. S. Craig\n|title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n|origyear=1974\n|edition=2nd\n|year=1989\n|publisher=Parliamentary Research Services\n|location=Chichester\n|isbn=0-900178-27-2\n|page=157\n}}</ref> aged 69.<ref name=\"rayment\" />\n\n==Background==\nCairns was born in Sunderland, the son of Thomas Cairns of Forfarshire. He was educated privately. In 1880 he married Isabella Dixon.<ref name=\"Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1907\">Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1907</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nCairns was chief partner of Cairns, Noble & Co., shipowners and merchants. He was Vice President of the Shipowners International Association.<ref name=\"The Liberal Year Book, 1907\">The Liberal Year Book, 1907</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCairns was a member of the Newcastle School Board from 1892-99. He was elected to Newcastle City Council in 1896. He was appointed as a [[Justice of the peace]] for Newcastle. He was active in the Liberal Party as Vice Chairman of the Executive Committee of the Northern Liberal Federation.<ref name=\"The Liberal Year Book, 1907\"/> He was Liberal candidate for the two member Newcastle-upon-Tyne division at the 1906 General Election. He ran in tandem with a labour candidate and together they took both seats from the Conservatives.<ref>British Parliamentary Election Results 1885-1918, FWS Craig</ref> Cairns was in favour of housing reform, social legislation and [[Women's suffrage in the United Kingdom|Women's suffrage]].<ref name=\"Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1907\"/>\n\n===Electoral record===\n{{Election box begin|title=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|General election January 1906]]<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Labour Representation Committee (1900)\n|candidate={{Y}} [[Walter Hudson (politician)|Walter Hudson]]\n|votes=18,869\n|percentage=31.1\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate={{Y}}Thomas Cairns\n|votes=18,423\n|percentage=30.5\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Walter Richard Plummer]]\n|votes=11,942\n|percentage=19.8\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party=Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate=[[Sir George Renwick, 1st Baronet|George Renwick]]\n|votes=11,223\n|percentage=18.6\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes=\n|percentage=84.6\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=6,927\n|percentage=11.3\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n|winner=Labour Representation Committee (1900)\n|loser=Conservative Party (UK)\n|swing=\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes=6,481\n|percentage=10.7\n|change=\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n|winner=Liberal Party (UK)\n|loser=Conservative Party (UK)\n|swing=\